"Woodroffe C.D., Brooke B.P., Linklater M., Kennedy D.M., Jones B.G., Buchanan C., Mleczko R., Hua Q., Zhao J.-X.","Response of coral reefs to climate change: Expansion and demise of the southernmost pacific coral reef",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","15", L15602,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL044067,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955482424&partnerID=40&md5=81d66abadbaaad3d2b5f938343cba4fe","School of Earth and Environmental Sciences, University of Wollongong, Wollongong, NSW 2522, Australia; Geoscience Australia, GPO Box 378, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia; School of Geography, Environment and Earth Sciences, Victoria University of Wellington, PO Box 600, Wellington 6140, New Zealand; Australian Nuclear Science and Technology Organization, Locked Bag 2001, Kirrawee, NSW 2232, Australia; Radiogenic Isotope Facility, Centre for Microscopy and Microanalysis, University of Queensland, Brisbane, QLD 4072, Australia","Woodroffe, C.D., School of Earth and Environmental Sciences, University of Wollongong, Wollongong, NSW 2522, Australia; Brooke, B.P., Geoscience Australia, GPO Box 378, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia; Linklater, M., School of Earth and Environmental Sciences, University of Wollongong, Wollongong, NSW 2522, Australia; Kennedy, D.M., School of Geography, Environment and Earth Sciences, Victoria University of Wellington, PO Box 600, Wellington 6140, New Zealand; Jones, B.G., School of Earth and Environmental Sciences, University of Wollongong, Wollongong, NSW 2522, Australia; Buchanan, C., Geoscience Australia, GPO Box 378, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia; Mleczko, R., Geoscience Australia, GPO Box 378, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia; Hua, Q., Australian Nuclear Science and Technology Organization, Locked Bag 2001, Kirrawee, NSW 2232, Australia; Zhao, J.-X., Radiogenic Isotope Facility, Centre for Microscopy and Microanalysis, University of Queensland, Brisbane, QLD 4072, Australia","Coral reefs track sea level and are particularly sensitive to changes in climate. Reefs are threatened by global warming, with many experiencing increased coral bleaching. Warmer sea surface temperatures might enable reef expansion into mid latitudes. Here we report multibeam sonar and coring that reveal an extensive relict coral reef around Lord Howe Island, which is fringed by the southernmost reef in the Pacific Ocean. The relict reef, in water depths of 25-50 m, flourished in early Holocene and covered an area more than 20 times larger than the modern reef. Radiocarbon and uranium-series dating indicates that corals grew between 9000 and 7000 years ago. The reef was subsequently drowned, and backstepped to its modern limited extent. This relict reef, with localised re-establishment of corals in the past three millennia, could become a substrate for reef expansion in response to warmer temperatures, anticipated later this century and beyond, if corals are able to recolonise its surface. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Expansion; Global warming; Sea level; Transuranium elements; Underwater acoustics; Uranium; Coral bleaching; Coral reef; Holocenes; Midlatitudes; Multibeam sonar; Pacific ocean; Sea surface temperatures; Water depth; Reefs; bleaching; climate effect; coral reef; global warming; Holocene; multibeam sonar; radiocarbon dating; sea level; sea surface temperature; uranium series dating; Australia; Lord Howe Island; New South Wales; Anthozoa",,,,,,"Andréfouët, S., Cabioch, G., Flamand, B., Pelletier, B., A reappraisal of the diversity of geomorphological and genetic processes of New Caledonian coral reefs: A synthesis from optical remote sensing, coring and acoustic multibeam observations (2009) Coral Reefs, 28, pp. 691-707. , doi:10.1007/s00338-009-0503-y; Banks, K.W., Riegl, B.M., Richards, V.P., Walker, B.K., Helme, K.P., Jordan, L.K.B., Phipps, J., Dodge, R.E., The reef tract of continental southeast Florida (Miami-Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties, USA) (200